Below is a step-by-step tutorial for building a simple website using HTML and CSS. This guide will help you create a basic webpage with a header, navigation menu, main content, and footer, and then style it with CSS.

────────────────────────────────
Step 1: Set Up Your Project Files

1. Create a new folder for your project (e.g., SimpleWebsite).  
2. Inside your folder, create two files:
   • index.html  
   • styles.css

────────────────────────────────
Step 2: Build the HTML Structure

1. Open index.html in your favorite text editor.  
2. Add the following basic HTML structure:
------------------------------------------------
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
  <head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8" />
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0" />
    <title>My Simple Website</title>
    <!-- Link external CSS file -->
    <link rel="stylesheet" href="styles.css" />
  </head>
  <body>
    <!-- Header Section -->
    <header>
      <h1>Welcome to My Website</h1>
      <!-- Navigation Menu -->
      <nav>
        <ul>
          <li><a href="#home">Home</a></li>
          <li><a href="#about">About</a></li>
          <li><a href="#contact">Contact</a></li>
        </ul>
      </nav>
    </header>

    <!-- Main Content Section -->
    <main>
      <section id="home">
        <h2>Home</h2>
        <p>This is the homepage of a simple website built with HTML and CSS.</p>
      </section>
      <section id="about">
        <h2>About</h2>
        <p>Here, you can add information about yourself or your website.</p>
      </section>
      <section id="contact">
        <h2>Contact</h2>
        <p>Provide contact details or a contact form here.</p>
      </section>
    </main>

    <!-- Footer Section -->
    <footer>
      <p>&copy; 2023 My Simple Website</p>
    </footer>
  </body>
</html>
------------------------------------------------

3. Save the file.

────────────────────────────────
Step 3: Create the CSS Styling

1. Open styles.css in your text editor.
2. Add some basic styles. For example:
------------------------------------------------
/* Reset some default browser styles */
* {
  margin: 0;
  padding: 0;
  box-sizing: border-box;
}

/* Body styling */
body {
  font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
  line-height: 1.6;
  background-color: #f4f4f4;
  color: #333;
  padding: 20px;
}

/* Header styling */
header {
  background: #35424a;
  color: #ffffff;
  padding: 20px 0;
  margin-bottom: 20px;
  text-align: center;
}

/* Navigation menu styles */
nav ul {
  list-style: none;
  display: flex;
  justify-content: center;
  margin-top: 10px;
}

nav ul li {
  margin: 0 15px;
}

nav ul li a {
  text-decoration: none;
  color: #ffffff;
  font-weight: bold;
}

/* Main content styling */
main {
  max-width: 800px;
  margin: 0 auto;
  background: #ffffff;
  padding: 20px;
  border: 1px solid #ddd;
}

/* Section styling */
section {
  margin-bottom: 20px;
}

/* Footer styling */
footer {
  text-align: center;
  padding: 10px 0;
  margin-top: 20px;
  border-top: 1px solid #ddd;
  color: #777;
}
------------------------------------------------

3. Save the file.

────────────────────────────────
Step 4: Open Your Website in a Browser

1. Open your project folder and double-click index.html, or right-click and choose “Open with” followed by your preferred browser.
2. Your browser will display the simple website with the styled header, navigation, main content, and footer.

────────────────────────────────
Step 5: Experiment and Expand

Now that you have a basic website:
• Experiment with different CSS properties (e.g., fonts, colors, layouts).
• Add additional pages or sections by creating new HTML files and linking them.
• Explore adding responsiveness with media queries if you’d like the website to look good on mobile devices.

────────────────────────────────
Additional Tips

• Use comments in your code to keep things organized.  
• Validate your HTML and CSS using online validators.  
• Consider learning more about modern CSS techniques (like Flexbox or Grid) to enhance layouts.  

────────────────────────────────
Conclusion

You have now built a simple website using HTML and CSS! This tutorial provided the foundation of a basic site. As you become more comfortable with HTML and CSS, you can further customize the site, add interactive features with JavaScript, or refine your design using more advanced CSS techniques.

Happy coding!

Below are three separate step‐by‐step tutorials on how to build a basic HTML/CSS website. Each tutorial shows a slightly different approach or set of best practices. At the end, we’ll merge the key ideas into one final, consistent tutorial.

──────────────────────────────
Tutorial 1: Basic Website with Inline CSS

Step 1. Create an HTML file  
• Create a new file named “index.html.”

Step 2. Write the basic HTML structure  
• Open “index.html” in your editor and add the basic doctype, html, head, and body tags.

  Example:
  ------------------------------------------------
  <!DOCTYPE html>
  <html lang="en">
    <head>
      <meta charset="UTF-8">
      <title>My Inline CSS Website</title>
      <style>
        body { font-family: Arial, sans-serif; margin: 20px; background-color: #f9f9f9; }
        h1 { color: #333; }
        p { color: #666; }
      </style>
    </head>
    <body>
      <h1>Welcome!</h1>
      <p>This is a basic website with inline CSS.</p>
    </body>
  </html>
  ------------------------------------------------

Step 3. Open the file in a browser  
• Save the file and open it in your web browser to see the result.

──────────────────────────────
Tutorial 2: Website with an External CSS File

Step 1. Create the project files  
• Create “index.html” and “style.css” in the same folder.

Step 2. Set up “index.html”  
• Write a basic HTML skeleton and link the external stylesheet using the link tag within the head.

  Example (“index.html”):
  ------------------------------------------------
  <!DOCTYPE html>
  <html lang="en">
    <head>
      <meta charset="UTF-8">
      <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
      <title>My External CSS Website</title>
      <link rel="stylesheet" href="style.css">
    </head>
    <body>
      <h1>Hello, World!</h1>
      <p>This website uses an external CSS file.</p>
    </body>
  </html>
  ------------------------------------------------

Step 3. Set up “style.css”  
• Open “style.css” and define your style rules.

  Example (“style.css”):
  ------------------------------------------------
  body {
    font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
    margin: 0;
    padding: 20px;
    background-color: #f0f0f0;
  }
  h1 {
    color: #2c3e50;
  }
  p {
    color: #34495e;
  }
  ------------------------------------------------

Step 4. Test your website  
• Open “index.html” in your browser to see the styling applied.

──────────────────────────────
Tutorial 3: Semantically Structured Responsive Website

Step 1. Create a structured folder  
• Create a project folder with an “index.html” file and a “css” folder containing “main.css.”

Step 2. Build a semantic HTML structure  
• Use semantic elements like header, nav, main, and footer, and include a meta viewport tag for responsiveness.

  Example (“index.html”):
  ------------------------------------------------
  <!DOCTYPE html>
  <html lang="en">
    <head>
      <meta charset="UTF-8">
      <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
      <title>My Semantic Website</title>
      <link rel="stylesheet" href="css/main.css">
    </head>
    <body>
      <header>
        <h1>My Awesome Website</h1>
        <nav>
          <ul>
            <li><a href="#">Home</a></li>
            <li><a href="#">About</a></li>
            <li><a href="#">Contact</a></li>
          </ul>
        </nav>
      </header>
      <main>
        <section>
          <h2>Welcome Section</h2>
          <p>This section contains an introduction to the website.</p>
        </section>
      </main>
      <footer>
        <p>&copy; 2023 My Awesome Website</p>
      </footer>
    </body>
  </html>
  ------------------------------------------------

Step 3. Create “main.css” inside the css folder  
• Define styles for the layout and responsiveness.

  Example (“css/main.css”):
  ------------------------------------------------
  /* Basic reset */
  * {
    margin: 0;
    padding: 0;
    box-sizing: border-box;
  }

  body {
    font-family: 'Arial', sans-serif;
    line-height: 1.6;
    background-color: #eef;
    padding: 20px;
  }

  header, footer {
    background-color: #333;
    color: #fff;
    padding: 15px 20px;
    text-align: center;
  }

  nav ul {
    list-style-type: none;
  }

  nav ul li {
    display: inline;
    margin: 0 10px;
  }

  nav ul li a {
    color: #fff;
    text-decoration: none;
  }

  main {
    margin: 20px 0;
  }

  section {
    background: #fff;
    padding: 20px;
    border-radius: 4px;
    box-shadow: 0 0 5px rgba(0,0,0,0.1);
  }
  ------------------------------------------------

Step 4. View your responsive site  
• Open “index.html” in your browser. Resize the window to see how the meta viewport helps make the site responsive.

──────────────────────────────
Final Converged Tutorial: A Consistent, Clean HTML & CSS Website

We’ll now merge the best practices (external CSS, semantic HTML, and responsive design) into one streamlined tutorial.

Step 1. Organize Your Project Files  
• Create a project folder and inside it, create:
  • index.html
  • a folder called “css” containing the file main.css

Step 2. Create Your HTML File  
• Open “index.html” and add the following code:

------------------------------------------------
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
  <head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>My Clean HTML/CSS Website</title>
    <link rel="stylesheet" href="css/main.css">
  </head>
  <body>
    <header>
      <h1>My Clean Website</h1>
      <nav>
        <ul>
          <li><a href="#">Home</a></li>
          <li><a href="#">Services</a></li>
          <li><a href="#">Contact</a></li>
        </ul>
      </nav>
    </header>

    <main>
      <section>
        <h2>Welcome</h2>
        <p>This website was built using semantic HTML and an external CSS file. It is responsive and follows best practices.</p>
      </section>
    </main>

    <footer>
      <p>&copy; 2023 My Clean Website</p>
    </footer>
  </body>
</html>
------------------------------------------------

Step 3. Create Your External CSS File  
• Open “css/main.css” and add the following styles:

------------------------------------------------
/* Reset basic styling */
* {
  margin: 0;
  padding: 0;
  box-sizing: border-box;
}

/* Global Styles */
body {
  font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
  background-color: #f9f9f9;
  color: #333;
  line-height: 1.6;
  padding: 20px;
}

/* Header, Navigation, and Footer */
header,
footer {
  background-color: #2c3e50;
  color: #fff;
  padding: 15px;
  text-align: center;
}

nav ul {
  list-style: none;
  margin-top: 10px;
}

nav ul li {
  display: inline;
  margin: 0 10px;
}

nav ul li a {
  color: #fff;
  text-decoration: none;
}

/* Main Content */
main {
  margin-top: 20px;
}

section {
  background: #fff;
  padding: 20px;
  margin-bottom: 20px;
  border-radius: 5px;
  box-shadow: 0 0 10px rgba(0,0,0,0.1);
}

/* Responsive adjustments */
@media (max-width: 600px) {
  nav ul li {
    display: block;
    margin: 5px 0;
  }
}
------------------------------------------------

Step 4. View and Test Your Website  
• Save all your files and open “index.html” in your browser. Check the appearance of your site and resize your window to test responsiveness.

──────────────────────────────
Conclusion

You now have three different tutorials:
 • Tutorial 1 (Inline CSS) – good for quick demos and small projects.
 • Tutorial 2 (External CSS) – better separation of HTML and CSS.
 • Tutorial 3 (Semantic HTML & Responsive Design) – recommended for professional projects.

The final converged tutorial combines the best practices from each method. Follow these steps to build a clean, maintainable, and responsive HTML/CSS website. Happy coding!

Below is a step-by-step tutorial for creating a simple website using HTML and CSS.

──────────────────────────────
Step 1. Set Up Your Project Folder
──────────────────────────────
• Create a new folder (e.g., "SimpleWebsite") to contain your project files.
• Inside this folder, you'll store all your HTML, CSS, images, and any other assets.

──────────────────────────────
Step 2. Create the HTML File
──────────────────────────────
• In your project folder, create a new file called index.html.
• Open index.html in your preferred code editor.
• Write the basic HTML structure:

------------------------------------------------
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8">
  <meta http-equiv="X-UA-Compatible" content="IE=edge">
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
  <title>My Simple Website</title>
  <!-- Link to external CSS -->
  <link rel="stylesheet" href="style.css">
</head>
<body>
  <header>
    <h1>Welcome to My Website</h1>
    <nav>
      <ul>
        <li><a href="#home">Home</a></li>
        <li><a href="#about">About</a></li>
        <li><a href="#contact">Contact</a></li>
      </ul>
    </nav>
  </header>

  <main>
    <section id="home">
      <h2>Home</h2>
      <p>This is the homepage of your simple website.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="about">
      <h2>About</h2>
      <p>This section contains information about you or your site.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="contact">
      <h2>Contact</h2>
      <p>Here you can add contact details or a contact form.</p>
    </section>
  </main>

  <footer>
    <p>&copy; 2023 My Simple Website</p>
  </footer>
</body>
</html>
------------------------------------------------

──────────────────────────────
Step 3. Create the CSS File
──────────────────────────────
• In the same project folder, create a file called style.css.
• Open style.css in your editor.
• Add basic styling to enhance the look of your website:

------------------------------------------------
/* Reset default browser styles (optional) */
* {
  margin: 0;
  padding: 0;
  box-sizing: border-box;
}

/* Body styling */
body {
  font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
  line-height: 1.6;
  background-color: #f4f4f4;
  color: #333;
  padding: 20px;
}

/* Header styling */
header {
  background-color: #35424a;
  color: #ffffff;
  padding: 20px 0;
  text-align: center;
}

header nav ul {
  list-style: none;
  display: flex;
  justify-content: center;
}

header nav ul li {
  margin: 0 15px;
}

header nav ul li a {
  color: #ffffff;
  text-decoration: none;
}

/* Main sections */
main {
  margin: 20px 0;
}

/* Section styling */
section {
  background: #ffffff;
  padding: 20px;
  margin-bottom: 10px;
  border-radius: 5px;
}

/* Footer styling */
footer {
  text-align: center;
  padding: 10px 0;
  background: #35424a;
  color: white;
  border-top: 1px solid #eaeaea;
}
------------------------------------------------

──────────────────────────────
Step 4. Link the CSS to the HTML
──────────────────────────────
• In the head section of your index.html (as shown in Step 2), ensure you have the following line:

  <link rel="stylesheet" href="style.css">

This tells the browser to load and apply the styles defined in style.css to your HTML content.

──────────────────────────────
Step 5. View Your Website
──────────────────────────────
• Save both index.html and style.css.
• Open index.html in a web browser by double-clicking the file or right-clicking and selecting “Open with…”.
• You should see your styled website with a header, navigation, main sections, and a footer.

──────────────────────────────
Step 6. Tweak and Expand
──────────────────────────────
• Experiment with the CSS by adjusting colors, fonts, and layout properties.
• Add more sections or pages as needed. For example, create another HTML file (about.html) and link it to your navigation.
• Keep testing changes in the browser to see the impact instantly.

──────────────────────────────
Summary
──────────────────────────────
By following these steps, you have:
1. Set up a project folder.
2. Created a basic HTML file (index.html) with semantic sections.
3. Created a corresponding CSS file (style.css) to style your page.
4. Linked your CSS file to your HTML.
5. Viewed and refined your website in a browser.

This basic structure can serve as a foundation as you learn more about HTML, CSS, and dynamic web development. Enjoy building and expanding your simple website!
